# Usage Guide

This guide describes how to use AutoFish_backend after it has been built and opened.

## 1. Select a Target Application

Use the target application picker to select a currently running app. AutoFish_backend sends keyboard events to that selected target process.

If the target app is not listed:

- Make sure the target app is already open.
- Click Refresh.
- Select the app again before starting.

## 2. Configure Keys and Timing

The Keys and Timing section controls the main trigger action.

- Int. Key: the first key sent after a trigger.
- Fishing Key: the second key sent after the randomized between-key delay.
- Minimum delay / Maximum delay: randomized delay between Int. Key and Fishing Key, in milliseconds.
- Min before-key delay / Max before-key delay: randomized delay before the first key is sent, in milliseconds.
- Run duration: total monitoring time, in minutes.
- Cooldown: minimum time between accepted triggers, in seconds.

Key fields are capture fields. Click a key field, then press the key you want to assign. Supported keys include letters, digits, common US keyboard symbols, Enter, Space, Tab, and Escape.

## 3. Configure Realtime Audio Check

Realtime Audio Check displays recent audio volume activity.

- Realtime: the current volume value.
- Maximum: the maximum recent volume value.
- Volume trigger threshold: triggers the configured key action when Realtime volume exceeds this value.
- Fallback input: optional loopback input device, such as BlackHole 2ch.

On macOS 11 Big Sur and macOS 12 Monterey, use a virtual loopback input such as BlackHole 2ch when direct system audio capture is unavailable. Built-in microphones do not capture headphone audio and are not a replacement for loopback audio.

## 4. Optional Auto Lure

Auto Lure sends one configured key at a fixed interval while monitoring is running.

- Enable Auto Lure with its switch.
- Set Lure interval in minutes.
- Set Lure Key by clicking the key field and pressing the desired key.

The Auto Lure key uses a 150 ms key-up delay.

## 5. Optional Auto Log in-out

Auto Log in-out sends two configured keys on a randomized cycle while monitoring is running.

Controls:

- Enable Auto Log in-out with its switch.
- Log out: first key.
- Log in: second key.
- Min key interval / Max key interval: randomized delay between the two keys, in seconds.
- Min cycle time / Max cycle time: randomized cycle wait before the pair is executed, in minutes.

After the two-key action completes, the timer starts again and waits for the next randomized cycle.

## 6. Runtime Controls

- Start: begins monitoring and timers.
- Pause: pauses monitoring and background timers.
- Stop: stops monitoring, timers, pending key tasks, and active audio capture.
- Simulate Match: development/verification helper for exercising the trigger path when sample matching is available.

The app also stops automatically when Run duration is reached.

## 7. Runtime Log

Runtime Log records successful trigger events. It keeps a bounded visible history while the Matches counter tracks the cumulative count for the current session.

Each log entry includes:

- Similarity field.
- Before-key delay.
- Between-key delay.

When the trigger is volume-based, the similarity field may not represent an audio sample match.
